&lt;p&gt;
For reMIDI, what we'd like to see (or, better yet, hear) is a new
version of some MIDI file. Choose a MIDI file that you have lying
around (or download it from the Internet, plenty free ones to choose
from) and remix, add instruments, change the rhythm, add effects,
etc. until you get a significantly different song. Of course, just
swapping a couple of instruments by others won't be enough. Your
editing must include but is not limited to MIDI edits. After you get a
nice MIDI variation, you can render it to mp3 or wav and keep changing
it there. Here is an example from a previous year, by Élvio
Rodrigues: &lt;a href=&quot;reMIDI/before.mid&quot;&gt;before&lt;/a&gt;; &lt;a href=&quot;reMIDI/after.wav&quot;&gt;after&lt;/a&gt;.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
Post the original and changed files, plus a short description of the
changes you made. You can also attach an intermediate version to show
the evolution process to aid with your explanation of the changes you
made.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
You should present original work, and we may ask for
  improvements/changes before accepting the result, especially if the
  quality or originality requirements aren't met.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
A logo is an important part of the image of any entity or
corporation. Good logos help people recognize a company or product and
are an important form of branding. They should distill in a single and
simple graphic the ideologies and nature of what they stand for. Good
logos abound and are all around us:
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:15%;margin-right:15%;&quot;&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/apple_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/carrefour_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/deli_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/hp_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/ibm_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/lego_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/microsoft_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/mtv_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/pepsi_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/shell_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/superman_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/m_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:100px;&quot; src=&quot;CourseLogo/ist_logo.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
  For this challenge you'll need to create a logo for this course! And
  you'll need to do it as a vector graphic, in SVG (you can use
  Inkscape, for instance). There are many, many web pages that can
  guide you through the logo design process. Here's a few:
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://sixrevisions.com/graphics-design/70-excellent-logo-design-tutorials-and-resources/&quot;&gt;70 Excellent Logo Design Tutorials and Resources&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.1stwebdesigner.com/design/10-logo-design-tips/&quot;&gt;10
    Logo Design Tips for a Timeless and Creative Logo&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.logobee.com/feature22.htm&quot;&gt;LogoBee's Top
  10 Logo Design Tips&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.davidairey.com/5-useful-logo-design-tips/&quot;&gt;5 useful logo design tips&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://designshack.net/articles/inspiration/10-tips-for-designing-logos-that-dont-suck/&quot;&gt;10 Tips for Designing Logos That Don't Suck&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.davidairey.com/henri-ehrhart/&quot;&gt;Henri Ehrhart&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-uDnln3dp7E&quot;&gt;How to Design a logo - Time Lapse Logo Design&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
You can also take a look
at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ist.utl.pt/files/media/media-kit/Kit-Normas-IST.pdf&quot;&gt;IST's
  new logo usage guidelines&lt;/a&gt;.

&lt;p&gt;
Especially, do keep in mind that:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A logo is an abstraction, not a photo or a detailed illustration
  (especially on this day and age where simple is better)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A corollary of the above: scale your logo to postal stamp size. Does it still work? If not, it is too complicated...&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Simplicity goes for color, too&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A logo should have something to do with what it represents&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A logo should be memorable&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;
What do we expect in your post? We want a rendered PNG version of your
logo (add it in multiple backgrounds, etc. if it is versatile and you
want to show it off), an attached SVG file of the logo, and at least
two images of sketches and early versions/alternative ideas for the
logo, to show you didn't just sit in front of Inscape and drew the
first thing that came to mind. Optionally, you can craft a simple
&quot;logo usage guide&quot; as the one linked above (for IST). In the PNGs, 
above, you must include at least a &quot;postal stamp-sized&quot; version, 
to prove it works.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
As usual, you should present original work, and we the professors may
  ask for improvements/changes before accepting the result, especially
  if the quality or originality requirements aren't met.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
  For Zombies and Monsters the goal is for you to produce, using image edition,
  a monstrous version of someone! There are plenty of variations on
  this: demons, monsters, zombies, frog-men, ghosts, etc. Below is an
  example created by João Amaral, one of this course's students from
  last year:
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style='text-align: center;'&gt;
&lt;img style='height:350px' src=&quot;ZombiesandMonsters/notdemon.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style='height:350px' src=&quot;ZombiesandMonsters/demon.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
  In essence, we expect a more careful/professional looking result
  than what you may already be accomplishing in the labs or other
  challenges. If you can make it especially aesthetically appealing
  and/or amusing all the better (your own photo, or that of a
  colleague, perhaps?). If you take a photo a special word of caution:
  a low quality photo will make your job much harder (garbage in,
  garbage out...)
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
There are plenty online tutorials on how to do this kind of thing (use
different photos, obviously). The requirements, in short:
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Original!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;High quality (no visible discontinuities or differences in
  lighting, etc.)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Don't give us just the final result. In your post, please include
  the starting photo, end result and short description of the main
  steps you had to go through to get from A to B&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;As is true for all these awards, we the professors may ask for
  improvements/changes before accepting the result, especially if the
  quality or originality requirements aren't met.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Here are a few things you should not do, if you want to get your submission accepted with a good rating:
&lt;p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;

&lt;li&gt;
Painted over eyes. These don't look realistic. They look like a white/black/yellow/whatever circle instead.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;ZombiesandMonsters/white_eyes.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;ZombiesandMonsters/white_eyes2.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
These are ok, though. See the difference?
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;ZombiesandMonsters/white_eyes_good.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;
Simply applying filters or using some &quot;canned-effects&quot; app
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;ZombiesandMonsters/filters.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;
Flat textures. A real face has shadows and highlights. It is a 3D object. Just pasting in a flat texture isn't realistic. Texture lines should follow the face's curvature. Shadows and highlights must be in the right places.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;ZombiesandMonsters/flat.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;
Cartoony/pasted elements. Not in the very least realistic. The first below is also a good example of a flat texture (to avoid).
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;ZombiesandMonsters/pasted.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;ZombiesandMonsters/pasted2.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;


&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
  For Alien Invasion the goal is for you to produce, using image edition,
  a &quot;photo&quot; of a building/city of your choice being invaded by aliens!
  Fire, explosions, ray guns, running people, let's have it all (or
  some :))! An example can be found below:
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style='text-align: center;'&gt;
&lt;img style='height:350px' src=&quot;AlienInvasion/peace.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;img style='height:350px' src=&quot;AlienInvasion/war.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
  In essence, we expect a more careful/professional looking result
  than what you may already be accomplishing in the labs or other
  challenges. If you can make it especially aesthetically appealing
  and/or amusing all the better (alien invasion of IST, anyone?!)
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
You can do this using your own photos (probably much more interesting
and fun?) or using photos downloaded from the Internet. There are
plenty online tutorials on how to do this kind of thing (use different
photos, obviously). The requirements, in short:
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Original!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;High quality (no visible discontinuities or differences in
  lighting, etc.)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Don't give us just the final result. In your post, please include
  the starting photo, end result and short description of the main
  steps you had to go through to get from A to B&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;As is true for all these awards, we the professors may ask for
  improvements/changes before accepting the result, especially if the
  quality or originality requirements aren't met.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Take care with avoiding the following if you want your contribution to be accepted and graded well.
&lt;p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;

&lt;li&gt;
Simply applying filters or using some &quot;canned-effects&quot; app and, in general, overdoing it...
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;AlienInvasion/overdone.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;
Clearly pasted in ships/aliens/flames/etc. Not realistic.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;AlienInvasion/pasted.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;AlienInvasion/pasted2.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;AlienInvasion/pasted3.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;



&lt;li&gt;
Unrealistic settings. See below: wouldn't all those people be running away in panic? 
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;AlienInvasion/setting.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;



&lt;li&gt;
Get the light right. See those (pasted in...) flames, below? Why aren't the surrounding buildings illuminated by them? Same goes for beams, energy weapons, ship drives and the like. Things cast light and produce shadows!
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;AlienInvasion/light.jpg&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;


&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Start flexing your video editing muscles! You've all seen news
shows. You know the format: there's a reporter, in a studio, reading
some news story, during which they can show some images or video
illustrating what is being told. Your goal is to record something
similar, reporting on some news item, real or imaginary (&quot;this just
in! on a surprising move, the mathematics department passed 95% of
students this year&quot;). We want something simple but credible, at around
30 seconds in time. You can be the news anchor, or you can invite your
friend, neighour or parent to serve in that role. We'll be looking at
technical skill when shooting and lighting the scene, not your actor
skills.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Post a description of the techniques and tools you used to create the
video and the video itself. Be original, tasteful, and, as always, we
may ask for improvements/changes before accepting the result,
especially if the quality or originality requirements aren't met.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
A couple of things to keep in mind:
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
Light the scene well. You should be well lit, from the front. The
setup below is the ideal but, of course, beyond what we expect you to
do. If you have no other light, the front-center one is the one you
shouldn't forget. If you can manage, ensure the background is well lit
as well (backlight).  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://lowel.tiffen.com/studioSetups/index.html&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;Reporter/light.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;
Avoid cluttered backgrounds. Lots of bric-a-brac, etc. make it look worse. Choose your background carefully. If necessary, a solid color wall will do. Want to go a step further? Do it like they do in real life: &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chroma_key&quot;&gt;chroma-key&lt;/a&gt;.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://bigpictureshreveport.blogspot.pt/2009_03_01_archive.html&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;Reporter/busy.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;


&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Way back in the day, we didn't have fancy graphics cards, just
text-based terminals. This didn't mean we couldn't have graphics. We
just needed to do them using characters! Welcome to the fantastic
world of...

&lt;pre&gt;
  ___                                       ___               
 -   -_,   -_-/    ,- _~. _-_, _-_,        -   -_,         ,  
(  ~/||   (_ /    (' /|     //   //       (  ~/||         ||  
(  / ||  (_ --_  ((  ||     ||   ||       (  / ||  ,._-_ =||= 
 \/==||    --_ ) ((  ||    ~||  ~||        \/==||   ||    ||  
 /_ _||   _/  ))  ( / |     ||   ||        /_ _||   ||    ||  
(  - \\, (_-_-     -____- _-_, _-_,       (  - \\,  \\,   \\, 


&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Check out
the &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASCII_art&quot;&gt;Wikipedia page on
ASCII Art&lt;/a&gt;. Lots of relevant information and resources there (also,
as always, Google is your friend). This thing even predates
computers. I've seen it done using a typewriter in the 70s'. It has
been used for pictures but also for gaming, such as in the notorious
roguelike games &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nethack.org/&quot;&gt;nethack&lt;/a&gt; and,
more recently, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bay12games.com/dwarves/&quot;&gt;Dwarf
Fortress&lt;/a&gt; (some of the most complex and games with a deeper
gameplay there are):
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nethack.org/&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;height:300px;&quot; src=&quot;TextArt/nethack.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bay12games.com/dwarves/&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;height:300px;&quot; src=&quot;TextArt/dwarf_fortress.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;
Nowadays, we can even go beyond this! We have UNICODE, not just ASCII,
and with it a wealth of graphical characters and symbols we can
use. So, your task here is to produce some Unicode-Art! What could you
do? Some ideas:

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A map, for an imaginary roguelike game, such as the ones
  above&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A screen from an imaginary side-scrolling game (think classic
  Mario or Sonic games), but drawn in text&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;
What you &lt;em&gt;must not do&lt;/em&gt; is something like this:
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;width:500px;&quot; src=&quot;TextArt/photo.gif&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
That thing is a conversion of a photo to ASCII. It fails for two
reasons: it doesn't use Unicode, and it was automatically generated by
some program. You must do yours by hand, choosing your characters,
etc.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
So, the requirements for your work are:

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.evertype.com/emono/&quot;&gt;Everson Mono
    font&lt;/a&gt;, which is a monospaced Unicode font with lots of
    glyphs. &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;You should create your art as the only content in a stand-alone
  HTML file (with appropriate headers for UTF-8 and CSS for Everson
  Mono) or a Microsoft Word document.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Your art should prominently feature unicode characters&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In your post, include the file with the art and a image of it,
  inline in the post, to make recognition easier (a screen capture is
  ok). Also, in the text of the post, discuss the main things you had
  to do, the most interesting characters you used, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;We may ask for improvements/changes before
accepting the result, especially if the quality or originality
requirements aren't met.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;




&lt;!-- http://www.unipad.org/techinfo/screenshots/editor.html --&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
One of the ways to produce a 3D effect is to quickly alternate between
the images as if taken from the point of view for the two eys. Some
people call
it &lt;a hreF=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiggle_stereoscopy&quot;&gt;Wiggle
Stereography&lt;/a&gt;. Some examples below (taken
from &lt;a href=&quot;http://3erd.tumblr.com/&quot;&gt;3ERD&lt;/a&gt;
and &lt;a href=&quot;http://fuzzywobble.com/&quot;&gt;Fuzzy Wobble&lt;/a&gt;):
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;width:500px;&quot; src=&quot;3DGIF/foam.gif&quot;&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;width:500px;&quot; src=&quot;3DGIF/lemon.gif&quot;&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;width:500px;&quot; src=&quot;3DGIF/man.gif&quot;&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;width:500px;&quot; src=&quot;3DGIF/party.gif&quot;&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;width:500px;&quot; src=&quot;3DGIF/dragon.gif&quot;&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;
You get a sense of depth from parallax and object occlusion. We want
an animated GIF, two frames, using this effect. To make one, you need
either a stationary target or two cameras (smartphones?) you can place
side by side and shoot at the same time. If you only have one camera,
take one shot and move it slightly to the side before taking the
second one. The separation between photos should be roughly the same
as the distance between your two eyes. This works better if some
subjects are closer to you than others, to get that parallax effect
going, but not too much, otherwise the images will differ too
much. Then it is just a matter of creating the animated GIF.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Post a description of the techniques and tools you used to create the
GIF and the GIF itself. Be original, tasteful, and, as always, we
may ask for improvements/changes before accepting the result,
especially if the quality or originality requirements aren't met.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
You already created the logo in Course Logo. Now it is time to go one
step further. You should redesign the course's identity, as if it were
a corporation or some other organization. This entails creating a
logo, business cards, envelopes and stationery. It should have a consistent
image, and, of course, be aesthetically pleasing. 
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;margin:auto; text-align:center;&quot; &gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://mustbeprinted.com/post/29257614086/printeasy-stationery-set&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;CourseImage/image_sample.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Plenty of inspiration online, including the ones shown at:

&lt;ul&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.designyourway.net/blog/identity-and-branding/letterhead-and-logo-design-inspiration-60-cool-examples/&quot;&gt;Letterhead And Logo Design Inspiration - 60+ Cool Examples&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.djavupixel.com/design/logo/corporate-identity-design-great-examples/&quot;&gt;7 great examples of Corporate identity design done right&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

Some of the links for the &lt;a href=&quot;CourseLogo.html&quot;&gt;Course Logo&lt;/a&gt;
assignment might help as well.
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;
We want:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Inline in the post, an image such as the one above showcasing your results&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The logo SVG file (yes, you probably have this already, but it is
  part of the overall image, so... Also, you may need to update it to
  match the rest of the elements)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A pdf file for a sample business card&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A pdf file for a stationery page&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A pdf file for an envelope&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In the post, some text describing the rationale behind the logo &amp;
image, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;
It is ok to change the logo from your previous submission. In this case we ask you to send again a complete set of studies and guidelines for the logo, including a usage guide where applicable. Take a look at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ist.utl.pt/files/media/media-kit/Kit-Normas-IST.pdf&quot;&gt;IST's new logo usage guidelines&lt;/a&gt;.

&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
As usual, you should present original work, and we the professors may
  ask for improvements/changes before accepting the result, especially
  if the quality or originality requirements aren't met.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
On this day and age, it is impossible to watch TV, read a magazine or
even stroll around town without being subjected to some form of
advertisement. A good advertisement requires good design, nice photos,
and good graphic editing. That is your challenge here. Here are a few
examples, but just turn your head around when walking home for hundreds
more...
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align:center;&quot;&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:300px;&quot; src=&quot;Publicist/sample2.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:300px;&quot; src=&quot;Publicist/sample3.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;img style=&quot;height:300px;&quot; src=&quot;Publicist/sample4.png&quot;&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Pick a product or service (real or imaginary) of your choice and
create an advert for it. We want something that could be a full page
spread on a magazine or stand on an outdoor sign. The product must be
recognizable and the poster must be appealing (you want me
to &lt;em&gt;pay&lt;/em&gt; for it, don't you?)
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Take care with the images you use (high quality) and the fonts you
choose (different fonts have different &quot;feelings&quot;). You may want to
include some vector graphics in there (Heineken's ad above shows
this).  You can submit your result in either pdf or png. Be sure to
include a short description of the product (if it isn't well known or
