&lt;img style=&quot;width:300px;&quot; src=&quot;Illuminator/sample3.jpg&quot;&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Your goal here is to produce a single page of illuminated text. Choose
a text of your liking. Look for examples of illuminated manuscripts
online for inspiration. You should then produce the page, including,
at least:

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Decorated initial capital. Lots of fonts can help here, such as
  &lt;a href=&quot;http://fontforge.org/sfds/toyfonts.html&quot;&gt;these&lt;/a&gt;, but
  plenty others as well&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Decorated borders and rules. These you should do in vector format
  (SVG) and then included in the final result&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Relevant images / illustrations. Do keep in mind a photo or
  similarly detailed image won't work (they didn't have cameras back
  then). So, more abstracted images are better. You could go vector
  or bitmap on this one&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;There must be a coherence in style. An art nouveau illustrated
  capital and a medieval border won't work. Having said this, you can
  choose whatever style you wish (even futurist, if you keep in line
  with the overall idea)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The graphic elements must bring the composition together. They
  must complement each other and graphically they must be aligned,
  interpenetrate, etc. Rule of thumb: if it looks just like a
  copy&amp;amp;paste of separate elements next to each other, it won't
  work. &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;



&lt;p&gt;
In your post, include a pdf or image of the result. Inline display a
  reduced size version, to facilitate recognition. Also, in your post,
  describe the different elements you used, and the tools and
  techniques employed. You should present original work, and we may
  ask for improvements/changes before accepting the result, especially
  if the quality or originality requirements aren't met.
&lt;/p&gt;

